properties.Summary:
Description: At 5:59 p.m. EDT, Environment Canada meteorologists are tracking a severe thunderstorm capable of producing very strong wind gusts, up to nickel size hail and heavy rain. ### Heavy downpours are likely to cause flash floods and water pooling on roads. Remember, severe thunderstorms can produce tornadoes. Severe thunderstorm warnings are issued when imminent or occurring thunderstorms are likely to produce or are producing one or more of the following: large hail, damaging winds, torrential rainfall.

properties.Title: Special Weather Statement In Effect
properties.Summary:
Description: The heat will persist until this evening. The combined values of temperature and humidity will give humidex values of 35 to 38. Limit physical activity; Drink lots of water, even before feeling thirsty, and keep cool. Check on elderly family members, friends and neighbours. Look for cool places, such as shade from trees, a swimming pool, a shower or bath, or an air-conditioned location like a public building. ### Please continue to monitor alerts and forecasts issued by Environment Canada. properties.Title: Heat Warning In Effect
properties.Summary:
Description: A warm and humid airmass will remain over the Maritimes through Wednesday. Maximum daytime temperatures near 30 degrees will persist over much of New Brunswick Wednesday, with overnight lows near 19 C providing little relief. Humidex values of 37 to 39 will also persist. Maximum temperatures along the Bay of Fundy, will be somewhat cooler. However, areas slightly inland are still likely to reach heat warning criteria over the next two days. Temperatures across northwestern portions of the province will cool somewhat on Wednesday as a trough of low pressure begins to move across the region. ### Heat warnings are issued when very high temperature or humidity conditions are expected to pose an elevated risk of heat illnesses, such as heat stroke or heat exhaustion. Please continue to monitor alerts and forecasts issued by Environment Canada. To report severe weather, send an email to NBstorm@canada.ca or tweet reports using #NBStorm.

properties.Summary:

properties.Title: Special Air Quality Statement In Effect
properties.Summary:
Description: Smoke is causing poor air quality and reducing visibility. Poor air quality due to forest fire smoke is expected to improve by Wednesday morning when the wind changes direction. ### Individuals may experience symptoms such as increased coughing, throat irritation, headaches or shortness of breath. Children, seniors and those with cardiovascular or lung disease, such as asthma, are especially at risk. If you, or someone in your care, develop symptoms, reduce strenuous outdoors activities where ever possible until the air quality improves. When outdoors, if your breathing becomes difficult or uncomfortable, stop or reduce strenuous physical activities. If you experience irritation of eyes, nose or throat, shortness of breath or other respiratory symptoms, you should take action to reduce your exposure to smoke. If you are feeling unwell and experiencing symptoms, contact your health care provider for advice. Issued jointly by Environment Canada and the Northwest Territories Departments of Environment and Natural Resources and Health and Social Services. For more information on air quality and your health, please visit the Northwest Territories Department of Health and Social Services at www.hss.gov.nt.ca/en/services/environmental-health/air-quality. Visit www.airhealth.ca for information on how to reduce your health risk and your personal contribution to pollution levels, as well as for current and forecast AQHI values. Please continue to monitor alerts and forecasts issued by Environment Canada.
Expires: 2019-07-31T13:22:43-00:00

properties.Title: Heat Warning In Effect
properties.Summary:
Description: A warm and increasingly humid airmass will remain over the Maritimes over the next few days. Daytime maximum temperatures are expected to reach 30 degrees Wednesday. Overnight lows tonight are expected to fall to near 20 degrees providing little relief from the heat. Maximum humidex values of 35 to 38 are expected. Temperatures across the island should cool down somewhat on Thursday as a trough of low pressure moves in from the northwest. Daytime highs on Thursday are forecast to be around 26 C with humidex values near 33. ### Heat warnings are issued when very high temperature or humidity conditions are expected to pose an elevated risk of heat illnesses, such as heat stroke or heat exhaustion. Please continue to monitor alerts and forecasts issued by Environment Canada. To report severe weather, send an email to PEstorm@canada.ca or tweet reports using #PEStorm.
